variables.documentation: The area of the ecosystem is defined as 1000 hectares.
variables.name: area

variables.documentation: A compounding process is used to depict hare births. The births flow is defined as the product of Hares and their natality. This process works just like compounding interest in a savings account.
variables.name: hare births

variables.documentation: In this external resource process, lynx are the resource underwriting the consumption of hares. Each lynx has a productivity, given by hare kills per lynx.
variables.name: hare deaths

variables.documentation: This equation calculates the average density of hares in the ecosystem.
variables.name: hare density

variables.documentation: Each hare in the ecosystem is assumed to produce 1.25 offspring (on average) per year.
variables.name: hare birth fraction

variables.documentation: A compounding process is used to depict lynx births. The births flow is defined as the product of lynx and their natality. This process works just like compounding interest in a savings account.
variables.name: lynx births

variables.documentation: This is a draining process. Some fraction of the lynx population will die each year. The portion that dies, in turn, depends on the density of hares in the ecosystem.
variables.name: lynx deaths

variables.documentation: On average, each lynx will generate .25 offspring per year.
variables.name: lynx birth fraction

variables.documentation: Initially, there are 50000 hares in the ecosystem.
variables.name: Hares

variables.documentation: The number of hares killed per lynx (per year) increases with the density of hares in the ecosystem. Note that when density is 0 (there are no hares), kills per lynx per year must be 0.
variables.name: hares killed per lynx

variables.documentation: Lynx mortality -- the fraction of the lynx population that dies each year, is assumed to depend on hare density. With fewer hares, a greater fraction of the lynx population will starve.
variables.name: lynx death fraction
